          "body": "Moses opens with a move that is unique to the eyewitness generation: 'I am not speaking with your sons who have not known and who have not seen' (11:2). The following five verses catalog what this generation's eyes have beheld — the discipline of the LORD, His greatness, His mighty hand, the signs in Egypt, the destruction of Pharaoh's army at the Red Sea, the wilderness provisions, and the earth opening to swallow Dathan and Abiram. The list is not nostalgia; it is a legal brief. Verse 7 closes the argument with the summation: 'but your own eyes have seen all the great work of the LORD which He did.' The force is prosecutorial — you cannot plead ignorance. You were there. What you saw obligates what you do. This is the deepest structure of Deuteronomic ethics: covenant obedience is not arbitrary rule-keeping but the morally appropriate response of a people who have seen a covenant God act on their behalf. Chuck Swindoll, commenting on the Shema's location just before chapter 11, rightly observes that love for God in Deuteronomy is always backward-looking before it is forward-reaching — the memory of grace precedes the demand of gratitude."
