          "title": "Egypt vs. Canaan: the theological ecology of dependency",
          "body": "The chapter's most intellectually striking argument is in 11:10-12. Moses contrasts the agricultural systems of Egypt and Canaan not merely to describe two climates but to demonstrate why Canaan is a uniquely covenantal land. Egypt is flat and Nile-fed; the farmer controls his water supply by foot-operated irrigation channels — a siphon-and-channel system where human ingenuity determines yield. Canaan, by contrast, is 'a land of hills and valleys' that 'drinks water from the rain of heaven.' In Canaan, the farmer cannot manufacture his own water. He is structurally dependent on the LORD's provision. The rain comes — or does not come — from above, and that is a theological statement as much as a meteorological one. Moses presses the implication: 'the Lord your God cares' for this land, and 'the eyes of the Lord your God are always on it' (11:12). The land is a watched land. What happens in it is noticed. This is why the blessing-curse schema (11:13-17) uses rain as its sign — in a rain-fed land, weather is covenant communication. Douglas Moo and the broader evangelical tradition rightly see in this passage a canonical principle: God sometimes places His people in conditions of visible dependency precisely so that the connection between obedience and provision cannot be obscured by human ingenuity."
