          "body": "Verses 13-17 form the chapter's most precise theological unit: a double conditional whose positive and negative poles are expressed in rain. If Israel listens obediently — loving the LORD and serving Him with all heart and soul (11:13) — then the LORD will give the early and late rains, the harvest of grain, wine, and oil, grass for cattle, eating, and satisfaction (11:14-15). If Israel's heart is deceived and turns to serve other gods (11:16), then the LORD's anger kindles, He shuts up the heavens, rain stops, the ground yields nothing, and Israel perishes quickly from the good land (11:17). The mechanism is not magic but covenant. The same LORD whose eyes are always on the land (11:12) controls the atmospheric provision through which that land produces. Peter Davids's observation on James 5:17-18 (Elijah's prayer and the rain) is illuminating here: rain in the biblical world was never a merely natural phenomenon — it was the most transparent expression of whether the covenant community stood in divine favor. The warning in 11:16 — 'beware that your hearts are not deceived' — echoes through Hosea, Amos, and ultimately the exile. Israel did enter the land, did eat and be satisfied, and was then deceived, served Baal (whose cult promised rain), and the LORD shut the heavens."
